    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-07-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="157"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.01 M 31/201</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kellogg</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-07-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 31, 1924</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received August 11.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 623</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose a copy, in
                    triplicate, of a note dated July 29, 1924, from the Foreign Office regarding the
                    proposed treaties affecting the former German territories in Central Africa (B
                    Mandates). …</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Ambassador:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">F. A. Sterling</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Embassy</hi>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The British Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs</hi>
                            (<persName type="from">
                            <hi rend="italic">MacDonald</hi>
                        </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the American Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                            type="to">
                            <hi rend="italic">Kellogg</hi>
                        </persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-07-29">
                                <hi rend="italic">July 29, 1924</hi>
                            </date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. W5896/23/98</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Your Excellency</hi>: You recently enquired whether His
                        Majesty’s Government were in a position to reply to Your Excellency’s note
                            <pb facs="0290" n="196" xml:id="pg_196"/> of the 18th February last<note
                            n="9" xml:id="d157fn9">See telegram no. 39, Feb. 16, to the Ambassador
                            in Great Britain, <ref target="#pg_193">p. 193</ref>.</note> regarding
                        the proposed treaties affecting the former German territories in Central
                        Africa now administered by His Majesty’s Government under mandate on behalf
                        of the League of Nations, and to proceed to the conclusion of those
                        treaties.</p>
                    <p>2. I have the honor to state that His Majesty’s Government would prefer to
                        postpone their final answer to the note in question until a more advanced
                        stage has been reached in the negotiation of the treaty relating to the
                        British mandate in Palestine. Their views on the latest proposals of the
                        United States Government in regard to that matter were communicated to you
                        in my note of the 17th instant.<note n="10" xml:id="d157fn10">
                            <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_208">p. 208</ref>.</note>
                    </p>
                    <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                    <closer>(For the Secretary of State),<lb/>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">G. H. Villiers</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
